content.description: Start on the far right of the boulder on a right sidepull and a descent foot and traverse left to the start of desperado.

The must do for the grade at Malibu tunnels.  On this side of the boulder, there are many variations or sit starts - but this listed route serves as the stand start.  Depending on the year, the amount of sand at the landing will determine if it's a stand start, jump start, or pad stacking jump start.  No matter, start with the left hand in the interesting looking pocket and the right hand on the sidepull and go up the obvious weakness in the rock.
content.protection: Pad.  possibly more for the start for stacking.
content.location: On the east side of the boulder.  It's easiest to find this route with its left hand starting hold - a very unique pocket.

content.description:
Start using the huge low hueco and get to the jug. From there, paste the feet and reach for the blind crimp. Finish with a committing slab topout.

The book has this as V4 but it feels harder. The move to the jug feels like V5.
content.protection: A few pads and spotters. The recent flooding has revealed a large boulder right at the landing and some smaller rocks around it. As long as you put a few pads down it should be ok.
content.location: On the arete left of the prow.

content.description:
This is everybody's warmup, cool down, and sometimes something to get the ego backup after getting crushed on your project.

Climbs up the big south face of the Malibu lieback boulder staying on/in the crack the whole way up.

This climb also serves as the usual downclimb for the boulder unless you want to do some jumping off the backside.
content.location: S face of Malibu lieback boulder. Starts on a small ledge.

content.description: Start using the huecos on the right of the boulder and traverse left and up using sidepulls and small edges.
Very fun route that sit starts on the very large ledge.  Go up to the crimps, then big moves up to more holds.  Finish straight up.
content.location: This route starts on the large crocodile mouth looking ledge on the SW side of the Malibu lieback boulder.  Sit's in between Malibu lieback and the Avalon.
